  "scientific_question": "This is NOT a drug discovery test. It is a topology regime generalization test: In NSCLC, mTOR is the largest structural damper (delta_r=+0.049) and MEK1 is near-neutral (delta_r=-0.011). mTOR inhibitors outperformed MEK inhibitors in KRAS-dependent NSCLC lines (D3_v2 H2 CONFIRMED). In CRC, the topology flips: MEK1 becomes the largest structural damper (delta_r=+0.120) and mTOR becomes the largest structural anchor (delta_r=-0.117). Question: do the SAME drug classes swap their relative efficacy in CRC, consistent with the topology change? If MEK inhibitors outperform mTOR inhibitors in KRAS-dependent CRC lines, ODS structural position preserves monotonic drug sensitivity ordering across topology regimes.",
  "operator_framework": "Perturbation operators: (1) CRISPR -- structural removal -- delta_r aligned (DISC_CANCER_4 r=-0.722); (2) kinase pathway inhibitors -- flow inhibition -- delta_r partially aligned within pathway module; (3) BET/transcriptional drugs -- state reprogramming -- delta_r misaligned (established exclusion). This experiment tests whether operator class (2) generalization holds across topology regimes.",
